g.aria-label: So, for the shallow gradient, the gas parCel’s temperature after compression is higher than the metal plate’s local temperature. As a result, it releases its heat to the plate. Similarly, after expansion and coming to it’s mean position, the parcel’s T is less than the plate’s T, thus transferring heat back to the parcel. The exact opposite happens for a steep gradient.

For a steep temp gradient, the temp. of the gas parcel after compression is still less than the local temp. of the plate and thus, heat is transferred from the plate to the gas. After expansion, heat is transferred from the gas back to the plate.

Aha, there you go! But you see this is for one single parcel’s interaction with tthe plate. However there are multiple gas parcels between all the plates in the tube. In the presence of standing waves, these parcels are coupled up and undergo simultaneous compression and expansions. Take 2 adjacent gas parcels where 1 gets compressed and the other gets expanded at the same time. In the context of experiment one, the 1st parcel (the one on the right) deposits heat to the plate while getting compressed. The adjacent gas parcel (the one on left) collects this heat from the metal plate as it expands. This then gets compressed resulting in a 3rd adjacent parcel picking up this heat. This cycle keeps continuing, effectively resulting in the transfer of heat from right to left! So heat actually goes in the direction of Rc to Rh.

So this corresponds to experiment 1.So in experiment 3, the reverse happens- a string of adjacent gas parcels in fact transfers heat to one another in the opposite direction resulting in a heat transfer from left to right.

Yup, you’ve pretty much nailed the coffin there. So these 3 cases of temperature gradients result in different directions of heat transfers between the 2 heat reservoirs. Each corresponds to each experiment Atharva had done!
